'''Adam Mitchel Lambert''' (born January 29, 1982) is an American singer, songwriter, and actor from [[San Diego, California|San Diego]], California. In May 2009, he finished as the runner-up on the [[American Idol (season 8)|eighth season]] of ''[[American Idol]]''.<ref> [http://www.americanidol.com/ American Idol]</ref> ''The Times'' identified Lambert as the first [[coming out|openly gay]] mainstream pop artist to launch a career on a major label in the United States.<ref name="www.timesonlineco.uk"> [http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article7013807.ece Adam Lambert, the new face of glam rock], Malcolm Mackenzie, ''The Times'', 4 February 2010. </ref>

Lambert released his debut album, ''[[For Your Entertainment (album)|For Your Entertainment]]'', in November 2009, via [[RCA Records]]/[[19 Entertainment|19 Recordings]].<ref name="rollingstone.com">{{cite web|author=Daniel Kreps |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2009/06/18/adam-lambert-teams-with-gagas-just-dance-producer-redone/ |title=Adam Lambert Teams With Gaga<U+2019>s <U+201C>Just Dance<U+201D> Producer RedOne : Rolling Stone : Rock and Roll Daily |publisher=Rolling Stone |date= |accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref> The album debuted at number three on the [[billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in December 2009, selling 198,000 copies in the United States in the first week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200#/charts/billboard-200?chartDate=2009-12-12 |title=Music Albums, Top 200 Albums & Music Album Charts |language={{ja icon}} |publisher=Billboard.com |date=2010-03-20 |accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.billboard.com/news/susan-boyle-sees-dream-soar-to-no-1-on-billboard-1004050070.story#/news/susan-boyle-sees-dream-soar-to-no-1-on-billboard-1004050070.story |title=Susan Boyle Sees 'Dream' Soar To No. 1 On Billboard 200|author=Caulfield, Keith|work= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=2000-12-02|accessdate=2009-12-28}}</ref>

==Early life==
Lambert was born in [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]].  He is the son of Leila, an [[interior design]]er, and Eber Lambert, a [[program manager]] for [[Novatel Wireless]].<ref name="ref121">{{cite news|last=Figuracion|first=Inigo|coauthors=|title=Inigo's San Diego Blog|pages=|publisher=About.com|date=2009-05-06|url=http://sandiego.about.com/b/2009/05/06/american-idol-front-runner-adam-lamberts-san-diego-beginnings.htm|accessdate=2009-12-05}}</ref> He has a younger brother, Neil.<ref>{{cite web|last=Peterson |first=Karla |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2009/may/03/1n3adam01733-former-san-diegan-snags-idol-spotligh/?metro&zIndex=92935 |title='Idol' sensation showed promise on local stage |publisher=SignOnSanDiego.com |date=2009-05-03 |accessdate=2010-07-27}}</ref> Lambert was raised Jewish.<ref>[http://out.com/detail.asp?page=3&id=26191 Adam Lambert: The Out Interview], Out.com, Shana Naomi Krochmal</ref><ref>{{cite video |people=Hen Liberman interviews Adam Lambert |date=15 November 2009 |title=Adam Lambert Answers Your Questions |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d59BgaKkdiU#t=2m48s |format=YouTube video |publisher=Guy Pines |accessdate=27 November 2009}}</ref>

Lambert moved to California shortly after his birth and grew up in [[Rancho Pe<U+00F1>asquitos, San Diego, California|Rancho Pe<U+00F1>asquitos]] in northeastern San Diego. He attended Deer Canyon Elementary School, [[Mesa Verde Middle School (Rancho Pe<U+00F1>asquitos)|Mesa Verde Middle School]], where he was a winner in the Airband competition (featuring [[Michael Jackson]]'s "[[Thriller (song)|Thriller]]"), and [[Mount Carmel High School (San Diego)|Mount Carmel High School]] (MCHS), where he was in theater, choir, and frequently performed vocals with the school's jazz band "MC Jazz".<ref name="penasquitos">{{cite news |author=San Diego Union-Tribune Staff Writer |title=<U+2018>Idol<U+2019> hopeful banks on theatrics to snag a spot |url=http://www.joesplaceblog.com/2009/02/24/adam-lambert-interview-with-sign-on-san-diego/ |date=24 February 2009 |accessdate=11 March 2009}}</ref> Some of his memorable MCHS performances included Frederick in ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]'' and "It's Only a Paper Moon" with MC Jazz. 

Lambert has performed in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] at Jewish events, singing songs such as "[[Shir LaShalom]]" at a 2005 tribute concert to [[Assassination of Yitzhak Rabin|assassinated]] [[Israel]]i [[Prime Minister of Israel|Prime Minister]] [[Yitzhak Rabin]].<ref name="mtv.com">{{cite news |last=Kaufman |first=Gil |coauthors=|title=Adam Lambert Talks About His Crush On Kris Allen| pages=|publisher=MTV.com |date=2009-06-09 |url= http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1613535/20090609/story.jhtml|accessdate=2009-06-09}}
</ref><ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1078460.html American Idol star Adam Lambert singing in Hebrew], [[Haaretz]], April 15, 2009</ref> Lambert attended Temple of the Arts in San Diego and has performed at the [[Kol Nidre]] service on the Jewish holiday of [[Yom Kippur]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Berrin |first=Danielle |url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/hollywoodjew/item/adam_lambert_the_jewish_american_idol_20090429/ |title=Adam Lambert: the Jewish American Idol &#124; Hollywood Jew |publisher=Jewish Journal |date=2009-04-29 |accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref> Lambert also performed in Jewish-themed ''[[The Ten Commandments: The Musical]]'' as Joshua, performing the song "Is Anybody Listening?"<ref>{{cite web|author=25 december 2007 |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lvwcJUhIa0U |title=Is Anybody Listening? (Adam Lambert) |publisher=YouTube |date=2007-12-25 |accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref>

==Early career==
Lambert has been a stage actor since he was about ten years old. He was cast as Linus in [[San Diego]]'s Lyceum Theater's production of ''[[You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Christopher |last=Rocchio |title=Adam Lambert dishes on making 'American Idol's Top 12 finals |url=http://realitytvworld.com/news/adam-lambert-dishes-on-making-american-idol-top-12-finals-8535.php |work=Reality TV World |date=2 March 2009 |accessdate=6 March 2009}}</ref> Around age twelve, he was cast in a production of ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]'' and continued performing throughout his teenage years including ''[[Hello, Dolly! (musical)|Hello, Dolly!]]'', ''[[Chess (musical)|Chess]]'', ''[[Camelot (musical)|Camelot]]'', ''[[The Music Man]]'', ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]'' and played [[Captain Hook]] in ''[[Peter Pan (musical)|Peter Pan]]''. At age 19, Lambert left the U.S. to tour with Anita Mann Productions for ten months before returning to the U.S. to perform light opera in [[Orange County, California]]. He was then cast in the European production of ''[[Hair (musical)|Hair]]'' and U.S. theater productions of ''[[Brigadoon (musical)|Brigadoon]]'' and ''[[110 in the Shade]]'', before being cast in the role of Joshua in ''[[The Ten Commandments: The Musical]]'' at the [[Kodak Theatre]] alongside [[Val Kilmer]]. Lambert was one of the few actors in the play that garnered a positive review.<ref name="broadway">{{cite news |author=Broadway.com staff |title=Headlines: Wicked's Adam Lambert Makes American Idol Top 12 |url=http://www.broadway.com/Wicked-s-Adam-Lambert-Makes-American-Idol-Top-12/broadway_news/5022245 |date=26 February 2009 |accessdate=6 March 2009}}</ref> From December 2006 to May 2007,<ref>{{cite web| title=Adam Lambert during The Citizen Vein | url=http://sukymurderglambertfanschile.blogspot.com/p/adam-during-citizen-vein-band.html}}</ref> Lambert briefly moonlighted as the front man for underground rock band The Citizen Vein with Steve Sidelnyk, [[Tommy Victor]] and [[Monte Pittman]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Monte Pittman on Adam Lambert and The Citizen Vein | url=http://www.ultimate-guitar.com/interviews/hit_the_lights/monte_pittman_id_love_to_see_adam_lambert_play_with_led_zeppelin.html}}</ref>  During this time Lambert also met producer [[Malcolm Welsford]] who helped develop his recording career since 2005. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanidol.wikia.com/wiki/Adam_Lambert |title=Adam Lambert <U+2013> American Idol Wiki |publisher=Americanidol.wikia.com |date= |accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref> He was then cast as the understudy for the part of [[Fiyero]] in the Broadway production company tour and Los Angeles casts of the musical ''[[Wicked (musical)|Wicked]]''.<ref name="broadway" /> Since 2004, he has regularly performed at the Upright Cabaret and the Zodiac Show, which was co-created by [[Carmit Bachar]] of the [[Pussycat Dolls]].

==''American Idol''==
Lambert auditioned for the [[American Idol (season 8)|eighth season]] of ''[[American Idol]]'' in [[San Francisco, California]]. In  a ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' interview he said his decision to audition for the show came after a week at [[Burning Man]] where he experimented with "[[magic mushrooms|certain funguses]]." He went on to say that "I had a psychedelic experience where I looked up at the clouds and went, 'Oh!' I realized that we all have our own power, and that whatever I wanted to do, I had to make happen."<ref>{{cite news|author=By<U+00A0> Alan Duke CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Music/06/09/adam.lambert.gay/index.html?iref=mpstoryview |title=Adam Lambert: I'm 'proud of my sexuality' |publisher=CNN.com |date=2009-06-09 |accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref> 

During his initial audition, he sang "[[Rock with You (Michael Jackson song)|Rock With You]]" and "[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]." Lambert had cited several musical influences, including [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Queen (band)|Queen]], [[David Bowie]], [[Michael Jackson]], [[Aerosmith]], and [[Led Zeppelin]].<ref name="AMG"> [http://allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=11:jcfqxzqgldse Adam Lambert Biography] Allmusic.com</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanidol.com/contestants/season_8/adam_lambert/ |title=Adam Lambert <U+2013> Season 8 Contestants |publisher=American Idol |date= |accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref>
In the semifinals, Lambert was voted into the Top 13, joining fellow Group 2 performers [[Allison Iraheta]] and [[Kris Allen]]. Lambert and Allen became roommates in the Idol mansion, with Allen stating it was due to their neatness.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://dannygokeyfansite.com/2009/03/21/more-american-idol-mansion-peek-us-weekly-issue/ |title=Idols move into the Idol Mansion.|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref>

During [[Michael Jackson]] week, he sang "[[Black or White]]" leading to praise from all four judges, with [[Paula Abdul]] predicting that he would go on to the finals.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://mjsbigblog.com/american-idol-season-8-top-13-performance-video.htm |title=MJs Top 13 Performances Recap & Review.|accessdate=2009-03-10}}</ref> The following week, Lambert sang a version of "[[Ring of Fire (song)|Ring of Fire]]". While [[Randy Jackson]], [[Kara DioGuardi]], and Abdul all liked his performance, [[Simon Cowell]] called it "indulgent rubbish".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://psychoticstate.blogspot.com/2009/03/american-idol-adam-is-in-ring-of-fire.html |title=Psychotic State: American Idol|accessdate=2009-03-17}}</ref> On [[Motown]] night, Lambert sang an acoustic version of [[The Miracles]]', "[[The Tracks of My Tears]]". The judges all liked it, and [[Smokey Robinson]], the week's mentor and the original singer-songwriter, gave Lambert a standing ovation. For his Top 8 performance, Lambert sang the 2001 [[Michael Andrews (musician)|Michael Andrews]] and [[Gary Jules]] arrangement of "[[Mad World (song)|Mad World]]". Because the show had exceeded its time slot, only Cowell gave a critique, which he did by simply giving Lambert a standing ovation. During the results next night, the other judges agreed that a standing ovation was the best critique of Lambert's performance.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.americanidol.com/contestants/season_8/adam_lambert/ |title= Performances and Reviews|accessdate=2009-03-29}}</ref> For his second Top 7 performance, Lambert sang "[[If I Can't Have You]]", delivering what DioGuardi described as his "most memorable performance", while Cowell described his vocals as "immaculate". Abdul was reduced to tears, with host [[Ryan Seacrest]] joking that Lambert had melted her into a "pool of Abdul".<ref>{{cite web|url= http://tvwatch.people.com/2009/04/22/idol-kris-allen-works-hard-to-stay-alive-on-disco-night/ |title=TV-Watch: Kris Allen "Works Hard" to "Stay Alive" on Disco Night.|accessdate=2009-04-22}}</ref> In the Top 4, Lambert was the first to sing, performing "[[Whole Lotta Love]]". Cowell commented, "that was one of my favorite performances...nobody can top that now", while Abdul, punning on the song's title, described Lambert's performance as "a whole lotta perfect".

Photos of Lambert romantically kissing another man surfaced while he was competing on ''American Idol''.  Initially shown and discussed by commentators on ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]'', the panel agreed that the images would likely have no impact on the competition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/12/fashion/12gayidol.html?_r=1&ref=style|title=Gay Talk Surrounds Adam Lambert of 'Idol'. | work=The New York Times | first=Guy | last=Trebay | date=2009-04-12}}</ref> Lambert confirmed that the photos were of him, stating he had nothing to hide and has always been open about his life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/Television/story?id=7336548&page=1|title=Adam Lambert: America's First gay 'Idol'?}}</ref> Mainstream media speculation centered on Lambert's sexuality; presuming he was [[gay]], he would be the first gay American Idol.<ref name="ewal"> [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20007164_20171835_20277643,00.html "Adam Lambert: Shaking Up 'Idol': He's the most exciting ''American Idol'' contestant in years: Huge voice, over-the-top theatrics...and that whole ''Is he gay?'' thing. He's a true original <U+2013> and just what the show needed." ] By Mark Harris, Entertainment Weekly,</ref><ref group=note>[[Clay Aiken]], [[American Idol (season 2)]] runner-up [[coming out|came out]] as [[gay]] in 2008. [[Will Young]], the 2002 winner of the inaugural ''[[Pop Idol]]'' contests on which all the other [[Idol series]] are based, pre-emptively came out as gay after he won.</ref> Much of the media focus regarded the readiness of ''American Idol'' voters for an openly gay winner.<ref name="ewal"/> Asked by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' whether the speculation surrounding his sexual orientation impacted the final vote, Lambert laughed and said "probably".<ref> [http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2009/05/22/adam-lambert-talks-idol-finale-sexuality-katy-perry/ "Adam Lambert Talks <U+201C>American Idol<U+201D> Finale, Sexuality, Katy Perry"] Chris Harris, Rolling Stone. 5/22/2009.</ref> He confirmed that he was [[gay]] in a ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' cover story interview shortly after he was named the ''American Idol'' runner-up.<ref> [http://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2009-06-09-lambert-rollingstone_N.htm Idol Adam Lambert 'comes out' in print], USA Today</ref>

For the top three show, where each of the three remaining contestants does a hometown visit and performance, Lambert sang both [[Michael Jackson]]'s "[[Black or White]]", and the [[Michael Andrews (musician)|Michael Andrews]] / [[Gary Jules]] version of [[Tears for Fears]]' "[[Mad World]]" at his alma mater, [[Mount Carmel High School (San Diego, California)|Mt. Carmel High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.mcsun.org/?p=3602 |title=American Idol puts on a show for MC| accessdate=2009-05-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://weblogs.newsday.com/entertainment/music/idol/blog/2009/05/adam_lambert_hits_san_diego_fo.html |title=Adam Lambert Hits San Diego|accessdate=2009-05-08}}</ref> Afterwards, San Diego mayor [[Jerry Sanders (politician)|Jerry Sanders]] declared May 8, 2009 "Adam Lambert Day."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/05/08/adam-lambert-get-his-home_n_200359.html|title=Adam Lambert Gets His Hometown Hurrah|accessdate=2009-05-08}}</ref>

On May 20, 2009, Lambert was announced as the runner-up for the eighth season of ''American Idol''. Lambert performed a medley of "[[Beth (song)|Beth]]", "[[Detroit Rock City]]", and "[[Rock and Roll All Nite]]" with rock band [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] during the final episode. His version of the winning single "[[No Boundaries (song)|No Boundaries]]" was later released on [[iTunes]] alongside ''American Idol'' winner [[Kris Allen]]'s version. Before the results were announced, Allen and Lambert joined together with [[Queen (band)|Queen]]<U+2019>s original guitarist [[Brian May]] and drummer [[Roger Meddows-Taylor|Roger Taylor]] to perform the anthem "[[We Are the Champions]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailycontributor.com/kris-and-adam-sing-we-are-the-champions/5058/ |title=American Idol Finale: Kris and Adam sing <U+2018>We Are the Champions<U+2019> (video) |publisher=Daily Contributor |date=2009-05-21 |accessdate=2010-03-24}}</ref> 

Upon winning, Allen said "Adam deserved this." Explaining this remark, Allen said that he thought Lambert deserved to win as much as he did, and that Lambert "was the most consistent person all year. He was seriously one of the most gifted performers that I've ever met."<ref name="deservedthis">{{cite web| url=http://www.americanidol.com/news/view/pid/1751|title=Kris Allen's Thoughts on Idol and the Future|accessdate=2009-06-07}}</ref>

